vectorData.altText: 17. With which body region are superficial lymph nodes associated?
That's right!  These other structures are deep to the skin.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Lymph forms throughout the body in the peripheral tissues, with the exception of the brain, bone marrow, and avascular tissues, such as epithelia and cartilage. All lymph passes through at least one lymph node, often many, before it is returned to venous blood.
Lymph nodes are abundant where lymph collects from body surfaces, external and internal, as these are sites of pathogenic invasion. Skin covers our external body surface; intact skin is a barrier to pathogenic invasion. Broken or compromised skin is an access

point for pathogens. Lymph from these surfaces collect in superficial nodes. Internal surfaces include those associated with our digestive and respiratory tracts, for instance, across which pathogens present in food and air may enter the body. Lymph from these surfaces collects in deep nodes, such as those associated with the aorta and trachea, respectively.
Lymph nodes are clustered in junctional regions of the body, such as the neck, axilla and inguinal region. In these locations, lymph nodes can limit the spread of antigen and disease from one body region to another. The physician has access to cervical, axial and inguinal lymph nodes for palpation, unlike deep nodes, such as those associated with the aorta and trachea.
